const CLASSES=[{id:1,date:"Feb 3",title:"What Is Tantra",subtitle:"History, principles & first mantras",content:{overview:"Tantra is a toolkit \u2014 not a belief system, but a system of practices that can be embedded in any tradition. It emerged ~500\u20131200 CE from a confluence of Vedic decline, devotional movements, and indigenous/folk practices (possession, animism, local deities). It took over everything: Hindu, Buddhist, Jain, even Sufi traditions absorbed its DNA.\n\nNon-dual Tantra flips transcendental spirituality on its head. Instead of escaping the world, the body, the senses \u2014 everything becomes a path to awakening. The body is the vehicle, not the obstacle. There is no separation between samsara and nirvana, sacred and profane, form and emptiness.\n\nThe goal: jivan mukti \u2014 liberation while alive, in this body. Recognition of your innate divinity and non-separation from ultimate reality.",concepts:[{heading:"The Tantric Toolkit",body:"These are the practice components that define Tantra. They were imported into yoga, Zen, and virtually every tradition they touched: visualization meditation, mantra practice (the defining technology \u2014 Vajrayana is sometimes called Mantrayana), pranayama and energy work (chakras, kundalini, nadis), ritual and offerings, guru relationship, deity yoga (merging with a deity \u2014 evolved from shamanic possession), and sacred geometry (yantras, mandalas).\n\nAny one of these can be a standalone path. But the toolkit is designed to snap together synergistically \u2014 visualization + mantra + pranayama + devotion creates something much stronger than any single component."},{heading:"What We\u2019re Doing Here",body:"This course is non-denominational, non-traditional, non-dual Tantra. We draw from both Hindu and Buddhist sources. There\u2019s no guru relationship, no secrecy, no single lineage \u2014 which is itself a little bit tantric (forbidden, transgressive).\n\nThe approach: learn the toolkit, then you can enter any tradition \u2014 Vajrayana, Shaiva Tantra, whatever \u2014 and understand what\u2019s happening. In the meantime, the practices themselves are deeply powerful.\n\nTrade-offs: We lose access to practices requiring guru transmission and esoteric initiation. We gain universality and direct experience."}],practices:[{name:"First Mantra Practice",type:"mantra",instructions:"Choose ONE mantra. Do not try multiple in a single session.\n\nAvailable open-source mantras (no initiation required):\n\nOm Mani Padme Hum \u2014 to Avalokiteshvara (compassion). Pronounce: Ohm Mah-nee Pahd-may Hoom. Not \u201cMah-nee Pahd-mee\u201d \u2014 those are different letters.\n\nOm Tare Tuttare Ture Svaha \u2014 to Green Tara. Pronounce: Ohm Tah-ray Too-tah-ray Too-ray Svah-hah.\n\nOm Namah Shivaya \u2014 to Shiva (five syllables). Pronounce: Ohm Nah-mah Shee-vai-yah.\n\nRam \u2014 name of the Hindu avatar. Can be repeated solo.\n\nSoham Hansaha \u2014 \u201cI am That, That is me.\u201d Pronounce: So-hum Huhn-sah-hah. The final \u2018ha\u2019 is barely an exhalation. Best default choice if you\u2019re unsure \u2014 it\u2019s formless, works for any tradition.\n\nSit in meditation posture. Repeat the mantra mentally (silent is most powerful, but aloud is fine when learning). Focus on the sound. Five minutes minimum. If you don\u2019t know which to choose: use Soham Hansaha."}],warnings:[],keyQuote:"For every Tantric teaching, there\u2019s 600 opposite Tantric teachings. Everything clashes. You just get used to that."}},{id:2,date:"Feb 10",title:"Japa & Mala",subtitle:"Mantra recitation technique & the rosary",content:{overview:"Japa means \u201cwhispering\u201d or \u201cmuttering\u201d \u2014 the act of reciting mantra. Mala means \u201ccircle\u201d or \u201cgarland\u201d \u2014 the rosary used for counting. Both terms are identical in Hindu and Buddhist usage.\n\nMantra practice is shamatha \u2014 it stabilizes and concentrates the mind. But it\u2019s also devotional: you\u2019re not just repeating sounds, you\u2019re invoking the deity or energy the mantra represents. These two aspects (concentration + devotion) together are what make it so powerful.",concepts:[{heading:"The Mala",body:"108 beads in both Hindu and Buddhist traditions. Half-malas (54) and quarter-malas (27) exist. There are actually 109 beads \u2014 the extra one is the guru bead (counter bead) with the tassel. It tells you when you\u2019ve completed one round.\n\nWhen you reach the guru bead, you never cross over it. Flip the mala around and go back the way you came. Keep the mala elevated \u2014 don\u2019t drag it on the ground. Your practice mala is a sacred object: don\u2019t wear it casually, don\u2019t lend it out, wrap it in cloth when not in use.\n\nEmergency mala (no beads): use your thumb to count the 12 segments of your four fingers (3 joints \u00d7 4 fingers). Nine rounds of 12 = 108."},{heading:"Four Levels of Recitation",body:"From least to most powerful (counterintuitively): aloud in a group (powerful through collective energy), aloud solo (weakest individual \u2014 mouth automates, mind wanders), whispered/muttered (the literal meaning of \u201cjapa\u201d), silent mental recitation (strongest \u2014 mind is doing the work), and ultra-subtle (mantra is barely there, almost unconscious, but still present).\n\nYour goal: get to silent mental recitation. Your mouth shouldn\u2019t be involved."},{heading:"Walking Mantra",body:"Replace your default mode network chatter with mantra throughout the day. Research shows default mode activity correlates strongly with negative mood. Simply substituting mantra for idle thinking measurably improves mood over time. No mala needed, no focused concentration \u2014 just keep it running in the background."}],practices:[{name:"Daily Japa Practice",type:"mantra",diagram:"mala",instructions:"Choose your mantra. Sit in meditation posture.\n\nWith mala: count through 5 malas (5 \u00d7 108 = 540 repetitions). Use odd numbers of rounds. Without mala: set a timer for 5\u20137 minutes. Focus entirely on the mantra.\n\nFocus point: third eye (between and slightly above the eyebrows). Feel the spot, place the mantra there.\n\nSpeed: slow enough that each syllable is clear. Don\u2019t rush to get through numbers. Mood: devotional \u2014 you\u2019re invoking something, not just making sounds. Heart open, mind focused.\n\nAfter: sit silently for a minute. Notice the shift. Also: do the mantra while walking, waiting, anytime you\u2019re not actively thinking."}],warnings:[],keyQuote:"It\u2019s incredibly important to remember this is a devotional practice. You\u2019re not just repeating words \u2014 you\u2019re invoking deity energy."}},{id:3,date:"Feb 17",title:"Prana & the Energy Body",subtitle:"Subtle anatomy, nadis, and Ujjayi breath",content:{overview:"The subtle body (sukshma sharira) is not physical \u2014 you can\u2019t find chakras in a corpse. But it\u2019s not imaginary either. It occupies a category called \u201csubtle\u201d or \u201cimaginal\u201d: when you work with it, powerful real effects occur. The physical body is an echo or expression of the energy body, not the other way around.\n\nPrana is life force \u2014 the Sanskrit cognate of Latin anima, Greek pneuma, Chinese chi, Tibetan lung. It\u2019s responsible for every activity: movement, breathing, circulation, digestion, thinking. It\u2019s closely linked to both breath and mind: control one and you influence the others.",concepts:[{heading:"The Three Main Channels",body:"Sushumna Nadi (Central Channel / Madhya Nadi) runs straight up the center of the body from perineum to at least the third eye. When energy flows here, non-dual awareness arises. This is the goal of all tantric energy practice.\n\nIda Nadi (left, lunar, cool, parasympathetic) and Pingala Nadi (right, solar, hot, sympathetic) represent all dualisms of existence. Most of the time, your energy runs in these side channels \u2014 that\u2019s why you\u2019re locked in dualistic experience. The whole point is to coax energy out of the side channels and into the central channel. Even a little energy in the sushumna creates profoundly still, non-dual awareness."}],practices:[{name:"Ujjayi Pranayama (Victorious Breath)",type:"pranayama",instructions:"The simplest pranayama. Foundational.\n\nSit upright, spine erect. Breathe through your nose (always nose for pranayama). Breathe in normally \u2014 nice, slow, deep breath. On the exhale, slightly constrict your throat \u2014 the same muscle action as whispering, but with mouth closed. You\u2019ll hear a soft hiss.\n\nThe constriction is in the THROAT, not the back of the nose. Think: \u201cwhisper with your mouth closed.\u201d\n\nDuration: 3\u20135 minutes before meditation. Can be done throughout the day.\n\nEffects: calming, centering, clears the mind. May partially work by preventing sub-vocalization.\n\nOptional add-ons: do your mantra simultaneously, focus on the third eye, gradually lengthen the exhale relative to the inhale."}],warnings:["Pranayama is physically powerful. Start gentle. Build slowly over months/years, not days.","If you feel dizzy, faint, or nauseous \u2014 stop for that session.","Like weightlifting: don\u2019t max out once a year. Do moderate practice consistently."],keyQuote:"Where the breath flows, the mind follows. Where the prana rests, awareness awakens."}},{id:4,date:"Feb 24",title:"Pranayama & the Science of Breath",subtitle:"CO\u2082, the Bohr effect, and Anulom Vilom",content:{overview:"The modern science of pranayama is primarily about carbon dioxide, not oxygen. Your blood oxygen is always 96\u201399% saturated \u2014 pranayama barely changes it. What changes massively is CO\u2082 levels, and your body\u2019s sensors detect CO\u2082, not O\u2082.\n\nThe Bohr effect: higher CO\u2082 in the blood causes more oxygen to be released into tissues. So paradoxically, practices that increase CO\u2082 (slow breathing, breath holds) actually deliver MORE oxygen to the brain and body.",concepts:[{heading:"Three Categories of Pranayama",body:"Slow breathing (Ujjayi, Anulom Vilom) enhances parasympathetic response \u2014 relaxation + focus + alertness simultaneously. Best bang for your buck. Fast breathing (Bhastrika, Kapalabhati) rapidly expels CO\u2082, triggers mild sympathetic activation \u2014 energy boost + mental clarity. Eustress that trains resilience. Breath retention (Kumbhaka \u2014 covered later) increases CO\u2082, causes vasodilation, enhanced oxygen delivery. The most powerful category and the original meaning of \u201cpranayama.\u201d"},{heading:"Nose Breathing",body:"Always breathe through your nose unless a specific technique says otherwise. Nasal breathing increases nitric oxide (vasodilation, antibacterial, antiviral). Mouth breathing chronically lowers CO\u2082 tolerance, physically narrows nasal passages over time, and disrupts sleep. Required reading: \u201cBreath\u201d by James Nestor and \u201cThe Oxygen Advantage\u201d by Patrick McKeown."}],practices:[{name:"Anulom Vilom (Alternate Nostril Breathing)",type:"pranayama",diagram:"nostril",instructions:"The single most important pranayama in the course. Also called Nadi Shodhana \u2014 \u201ccleansing the nadis.\u201d\n\nPreparation: clear your nostrils (neti pot with salt water, or the breath-hold nose-clearing method from Oxygen Advantage).\n\nHand position: right hand. Close right nostril with thumb, left nostril with two middle fingers.\n\nTechnique: close right nostril, breathe IN through left. Close left nostril, breathe OUT through right. Keep left closed, breathe IN through right. Close right nostril, breathe OUT through left. That\u2019s one round. Always start left-in, always end left-out.\n\nRatio: start with equal in/out (1:1). For stronger effect, make exhale twice as long as inhale (1:2). Count using seed syllables or numbers.\n\nDuration: start with 3\u20135 minutes. Can build to 30\u201340 minutes."},{name:"Bhastrika (Bellows Breath)",type:"pranayama",instructions:"Fast belly breathing \u2014 equal pressure in and out. NOT from the chest or shoulders.\n\nSit upright. Nose clear. Breathe rapidly from the belly \u2014 equal in and out, like a bellows. Start slow until smooth, then increase speed. Avoid stuttering or jerking. The belly moves; the shoulders don\u2019t.\n\nDuration: start with 30 seconds to 1 minute. Always follow with a slow/regulatory breath (Ujjayi or Anulom Vilom). Use before meditation, not before bed."}],warnings:["Empty stomach for pranayama \u2014 wait 2.5 hours after food, 30 min after tea/coffee.","Do not do fast breathing before bed (insomnia risk).","Sequence: fast breathing to activate \u2192 slow breathing to regulate \u2192 meditate."],keyQuote:"The idea is: activate energy, then regulate it. It\u2019s a system \u2014 not just more energy."}},{id:5,date:"Mar 3",title:"Kapalabhati & Energy",subtitle:"Skull shining breath, kundalini concepts, grounding",content:{overview:"Kapalabhati means \u201cskull shining\u201d \u2014 kapala (skull) + bhati (to brighten). It uses Bhastrika as a component, then adds a full exhale, full inhale, brief hold, and left-nostril exhale. The effect is a sustained, rising alertness that sneaks up over several minutes.\n\nEnergy (shakti) is the core concern of Tantra. We raise energy to cut through delusion \u2014 but we must channel it correctly, or it just amplifies neurosis.",concepts:[{heading:"Kundalini / Chandali",body:"Kundalini (Hindu) and Chandali/Tummo (Buddhist) are different names for the same phenomenon. Dormant spiritual energy stored at the base of the central channel \u2014 the \u201cleftover\u201d (shesha) from when prana created your body. When prana brings you into manifestation (pravritti), it binds you to the world through attention, body, desires, personality. The reversal (nivritti) is when attention turns inward, energy awakens, and rises through the central channel, dissolving dualistic perception at each level."},{heading:"Grounding Excess Energy",body:"Too much energy manifests as racing thoughts, insomnia, edginess, headaches, mania. Methods to ground: mentally draw energy down into belly (prana follows attention); slow, deep, rhythmic breathing; alternate nostril breathing for balance; offer excess energy as a gift to the earth \u2014 feel it drain out your feet; pray to your chosen deity or guru for help; use the earth element bija LUM; go sit on rocks outdoors and breathe slowly. Combine several for stronger effect. The cure for too much pranayama is always: stop, rest for days, let your system re-regulate."}],practices:[{name:"Kapalabhati (Skull Shining Breath)",type:"pranayama",diagram:"kapalabhati",instructions:"Requires competence in Bhastrika. A five-step process:\n\nStep 1: do 30\u2013100 rounds of Bhastrika at your comfortable speed. Step 2: on your last exhale, breathe ALL the way out \u2014 collapse the belly, empty completely. Step 3: take a full three-part inhale \u2014 fill lower, middle, upper lungs. Step 4: hold breath for 7\u201312 seconds. Step 5: close right nostril, exhale through left nostril.\n\nThat\u2019s one Kapalabhati. Do 3\u20135 of them.\n\nTiming: morning only for most people \u2014 this will wake you up for hours. Effects: elevated mood lasting hours, sharpened focus, increased metabolism. The full effect sneaks up ~5 minutes after finishing.\n\nDo not have coffee beforehand. Follow with slow breathing to regulate."}],warnings:["Kapalabhati is very activating. 3 rounds can charge an entire day.","If you can\u2019t sleep, you\u2019re doing too much. Back off for several days."],keyQuote:"You raise energy to cut through delusion \u2014 but if it\u2019s not channeled correctly, it just makes you more crazy and deluded."}},{id:6,date:"Mar 10",title:"Bija Mantras & Visualization",subtitle:"Seed syllables, bhavana, training the mind\u2019s eye",content:{overview:"Bija (seed) mantras are single-syllable sound-chunks without linguistic meaning. Unlike \u201cOm Namah Shivaya\u201d (regular Sanskrit), bijas are pure energetic phonemes \u2014 distilled mantra essence. They became the most powerful component of complex mantras during the Tantric era.\n\nVisualization (bhavana) is a defining practice of Tantra. In Tibet, the first meditation given to a beginner is \u201cvisualize a Buddha\u201d \u2014 not breath meditation. It provides instant feedback: the moment concentration lapses, the image vanishes.",concepts:[{heading:"Key Bija Mantras",body:"OM (AUM) \u2014 the primal bija, seed of all seeds, present in virtually every mantra, bija of the third eye.\n\nGoddess bijas (common prefixes): AIM (Saraswati), KRIM (Mahadevi), SHRIM (Lakshmi), DUM (Durga \u2014 protective).\n\nElemental bijas for chakra work: LUM (earth/Muladhara), VUM (water/Svadhisthana), RUM (fire/Manipura), YUM (air/Anahata), HUM (space/Vishuddha).\n\nVajrayana bijas: HUM (dispels delusion), HRIH (Avalokiteshvara/Amitabha)."},{heading:"Visualization Method",body:"Sustaining: bring image to mind, when it fades reboot it, if you can\u2019t recall it open eyes and look at the original. Exactly like losing the breath and coming back.\n\nRefining: over weeks, work on clarity, brightness, detail. Focus on one part at a time until each is vivid.\n\nMulti-sensory: layer in the mantra sound + body sensation at the location + emotional mood.\n\nThe key insight: visualization happens in your MIND/MEMORY, not your eyes. Think of it like remembering a face. Most people who think they have aphantasia just haven\u2019t practiced."}],practices:[{name:"Basic Visualization Practice",type:"visualization",instructions:"Start simple: look at the palm of your hand at arm\u2019s length. Study it. Close your eyes. Bring up the image. When it fades, reboot. When you can\u2019t reboot, open eyes and look again.\n\nIntermediate: visualize a white circle of light at your third eye. Not with your eyes \u2014 with your mind.\n\nAdvanced: visualize the OM symbol in red on a white light circle at your third eye. Simultaneously chant OM mentally and feel the third eye spot.\n\nDo this daily for a month and you\u2019ll be surprised at the improvement."}],warnings:["Visualization is fabrication, not reification. You know it\u2019s imaginary \u2014 and this insight extends to seeing all experience as mind-made."],keyQuote:"We are not reifying. We are learning that our mind can create things \u2014 and eventually you see the whole rest of the world as something you\u2019re making up with your mind."}},{id:7,date:"Mar 17",title:"Kumbhaka",subtitle:"Breath retention \u2014 internal, external, spontaneous",content:{overview:"Kumbhaka means \u201cpot\u201d or \u201cvessel\u201d \u2014 holding breath like air in a pot. This is probably the original meaning of \u201cpranayama.\u201d It\u2019s the single biggest upgrade to your breath practice \u2014 a multiplier on everything else. Also the most dangerous if overdone.",concepts:[{heading:"Three Types of Breath Retention",body:"Antara Kumbhaka (internal retention \u2014 full lungs): energizing, clarifying. Increases CO\u2082 \u2192 vasodilation \u2192 more oxygen to tissues.\n\nBahya Kumbhaka (external retention \u2014 empty lungs): calming, soothing, purifying, grounding. Detoxifies, cleans nadis. Essential for bandha practice.\n\nKevala Kumbhaka (spontaneous retention): not a practice \u2014 it happens to you. Breath simply stops during deep meditation. Sign of profound stillness."},{heading:"Signs of Overdoing It",body:"Physical: dizziness, tingling/numbness, headaches, pressure in head, heart palpitations, muscle cramps.\n\nRespiratory: gasping after release, chest tightness, excessive air hunger, yawning all day.\n\nNervous system: anxiety, restlessness, difficulty relaxing, insomnia, panic.\n\nIf any persist beyond a few minutes: do less next time. The cure is always to stop and rest."}],practices:[{name:"Samavritti (Box Breathing)",type:"pranayama",instructions:"Equal ratio 1:1:1:1 on all four phases. Uses both internal and external retention.\n\nInhale for N counts. Hold full for N counts. Exhale for N counts. Hold empty for N counts. Start with 4-count. Should feel relaxed, not strained. Can mix with Ujjayi. Great for stress reduction, anxiety management, pre-meditation, falling asleep."},{name:"Anulom Vilom with Kumbhaka",type:"pranayama",diagram:"ratio",instructions:"Alternate nostril breathing with internal breath retention. The core advanced pranayama.\n\nRatio progression (inhale : hold : exhale) \u2014 beginner: 1:1:1 or 1:1:2. Intermediate: 1:2:2. Target: 1:4:2.\n\nWith a 4-count inhale at 1:4:2: inhale left nostril for 4, hold (both nostrils closed) for 16, exhale right nostril for 8, then inhale right for 4, hold for 16, exhale left for 8. That\u2019s one round.\n\nDo Bhastrika first to make holding easier. End on left nostril exhale. Use whatever ratio keeps you relaxed with no gasping."}],warnings:["Contraindications: heart conditions, respiratory issues, anxiety disorders, pregnancy, epilepsy, glaucoma, hernias, acid reflux.","Build gradually. Never strain. Never gasp on release.","Practice in clean air \u2014 best outdoors near water/trees, or with an air purifier."],keyQuote:"Even doing really mellowly, it does a lot. That\u2019s why I keep saying be careful \u2014 because it works."}},{id:8,date:"Mar 24",title:"The Chakra System",subtitle:"Seven centers, elemental bijas, and meditation",content:{overview:"Chakras are energy centers along the central channel. The word just means \u201cwheel.\u201d There isn\u2019t one chakra system \u2014 there are dozens. The standard six/seven system we use is the most common in modern Hindu practice. The \u201crainbow colors\u201d everywhere are a modern invention \u2014 traditionally, colors correspond to elements.\n\nChakras aren\u2019t physical but aren\u2019t imaginary either. Working with them produces powerful, real effects.",concepts:[{heading:"The Seven Chakras",body:"Muladhara (root/perineum): earth element, bija LUM, traditional color yellow. Seat of dormant kundalini.\n\nSvadhisthana (sacral/pubic area): water element, bija VUM, traditional color white. Desire, creativity.\n\nManipura (navel/solar plexus): fire element, bija RUM, traditional color red. Power, will, digestion. Tummo works here.\n\nAnahata (heart center): air element, bija YUM, color green. Love, compassion, healing. Seat of the mind. \u201cUnstruck sound.\u201d\n\nVishuddha (throat): space/ether, bija HUM, color blue. Purification, communication, truth.\n\nAjna (third eye): no element, bija OM, color white. Wisdom, insight. THE enlightenment chakra.\n\nSahasrara (crown): no element, no bija, pure light. Not technically a chakra.\n\nAll bijas end with nasalization (not a hard M). LUM rhymes with \u201cgum.\u201d VUM is between V and W."}],practices:[{name:"Chakra Meditation with Bija Mantras",type:"meditation",diagram:"chakra",instructions:"Sit upright. Feel each chakra location. Chant the bija mentally or aloud. Spend about 1 minute at each center.\n\nAscending: Muladhara (LUM) \u2192 Svadhisthana (VUM) \u2192 Manipura (RUM) \u2192 Anahata (YUM) \u2192 Vishuddha (HUM) \u2192 Ajna (OM).\n\nDescending: reverse the order. Go up and down multiple times. Very energizing.\n\nOptionally visualize white light or the Devanagari letter at each center. You can also spend extended time on a single chakra \u2014 e.g., 30 minutes of just LUM at the root."}],warnings:["Some people get strong physical reactions (heat, emotion, nausea, agitation). If so, do less."],keyQuote:"Different chakra systems are different lineage approaches, not contradictions. They\u2019re just different ways people have decided to work with the energy."}},{id:9,date:"Apr 7",title:"Bandhas (Locks)",subtitle:"Root lock, throat lock, abdominal lock, Maha Bandha",content:{overview:"Bandha means \u201cbind\u201d or \u201clock\u201d (cognate with English \u201cbond\u201d). These are physical muscle contractions that contain and direct prana \u2014 they put the energy in a bottle. Combined with kumbhaka, they are a massive multiplier on pranayama. Also the most dangerous component if done incorrectly.",concepts:[{heading:"Why Bandhas Work",body:"They prevent prana from dissipating out the top or bottom of the body. They enhance breath retention by physically sealing the container. They push prana into the central channel. They help pierce the three granthis (knots) in the central channel. Over time, they can be done mentally rather than physically, which is even more powerful."}],practices:[{name:"The Three Locks + Maha Bandha",type:"bandha",diagram:"bandha",instructions:"Mula Bandha (root lock): contract the perineum \u2014 the muscles BETWEEN the anal sphincter and the urogenital muscles. Not your butt. Not holding your pee. The middle. Gentle lift upward. Can be held for extended periods. The easiest lock.\n\nJalandhara Bandha (throat lock): lift sternum slightly, pull chin back and down onto chest. Stops you from breathing \u2014 that\u2019s the point. Keep face relaxed. Don\u2019t clench jaw. If it hurts, do a gentler version.\n\nUddiyana Bandha (abdominal lock): the hardest lock. Can ONLY be done on an empty exhale. Exhale completely, lock throat, pull abdomen back toward spine AND diaphragm up under ribs. A visible concavity should form. Lean forward with hands on knees. Requires empty stomach (2.5+ hours). Builds core strength over months.\n\nMaha Bandha (the great lock): all three simultaneously on an empty exhale. Do Bhastrika first, exhale completely, apply root lock, then abdominal lock, then throat lock. Hold 1\u201310 seconds, release gently. 1\u20133 rounds is plenty."}],warnings:["Not good for high blood pressure \u2014 bandhas temporarily increase blood pressure.","Uddiyana Bandha can pull muscles in your back, ribs, or pelvis. Go extremely slow.","Do not lock your throat while doing Bhastrika."],keyQuote:"You\u2019re putting the energy in a bottle. Very noticeable \u2014 it just goes whoosh."}},{id:10,date:"Apr 21",title:"Cleansing the Nadis",subtitle:"Integrating kumbhaka + bandhas + bijas into Nadi Shodhana",content:{overview:"Everything comes together. Nadi Shodhana done with breath holds, bandhas, mantras, and visualization simultaneously. This is the full-system practice for clearing energetic blockages.\n\nThe blockages are described traditionally as karma; psychologically as somatic trauma/emotional holding patterns. Either way, the cleansing mechanism is the same.",concepts:[{heading:"Integration Pattern",body:"Layer 1: basic alternate nostril breathing (no holds). Layer 2: add kumbhaka with ratios. Layer 3: add bija mantras for counting and chakra focus. Layer 4: add bandhas \u2014 root lock on inhale, throat lock during hold, quick abdominal lock at end of exhale. Layer 5: add visualization.\n\nOnly add a layer when the previous one is muscle memory."},{heading:"Bandha Integration",body:"During Anulom Vilom with kumbhaka: on the INHALE apply Mula Bandha. During the HOLD add Jalandhara Bandha, keep root lock if possible. On the EXHALE release throat lock to breathe out; at the very end, do a quick Uddiyana Bandha for just 1 second, then begin next inhale."}],practices:[{name:"Full Nadi Shodhana",type:"pranayama",instructions:"Setup: empty stomach, clean air, seated upright, clear nostrils.\n\nSequence: Bhastrika (50\u2013100 breaths) \u2192 Nadi Shodhana with your comfortable ratio and layers \u2192 about 3 minutes \u2192 end on left nostril exhale \u2192 brief Bhastrika if needed \u2192 sit and feel the energy for 5+ minutes, then meditate.\n\nThis IS the main daily practice from here forward. Even basic alternate nostril breathing without add-ons is cleansing your nadis.\n\nEffects: lighter, brighter, thought activity greatly reduced. If emotions surface strongly, sit with them or stop and process."}],warnings:["If you feel manic/speedy afterward, you did too much.","Keep a journal: what you did, how it felt, how your day went.","Morning practice is best for most people."],keyQuote:"You want it to be that when you do this and meditate afterwards, it feels like you\u2019ve been in a retreat for a couple days already."}},{id:11,date:"Apr 28",title:"Advanced Nadi Shodhana",subtitle:"Chakra-by-chakra cleansing \u2014 the full sequence",content:{overview:"The culminating practice: Nadi Shodhana performed one chakra at a time, ascending from Muladhara to Ajna and descending back. Each chakra gets its own elemental bija mantra while doing alternate nostril breathing with kumbhaka and bandhas.",concepts:[{heading:"The Full Sequence",body:"For each chakra: one round of Nadi Shodhana using that chakra\u2019s bija as the counting mantra, while feeling/visualizing that energy center.\n\nAscending: Muladhara (LUM), Svadhisthana (VUM), Manipura (RUM), Anahata (YUM), Vishuddha (HUM), Ajna (OM \u2014 do twice since we skip the crown).\n\nDescending: reverse order back to Muladhara. One complete cycle is a full session."},{heading:"Kapalabhati Enhancement",body:"After Bhastrika in Kapalabhati, when you exhale completely (step 2), add a 1-second Maha Bandha before inhaling. Just a quick pulse of all three locks. Significantly potentiates the practice."}],practices:[{name:"Full Chakra Nadi Shodhana",type:"pranayama",diagram:"nadicycle",instructions:"The complete practice session:\n\nBhastrika (50\u2013100 rounds to prepare). Then ascend through chakras \u2014 at each one, do one round of Nadi Shodhana with that chakra\u2019s bija as counter, feeling the center, using your kumbhaka ratio and bandhas if ready. Do Ajna (OM) twice. Then descend back through all chakras.\n\nBrief Bhastrika to re-oxygenate if needed. Then sit for 5\u201310 minutes minimum \u2014 feel the energy, meditate.\n\nUse whatever ratio you can handle. Drop components if it\u2019s too much. The most important element is: feel the chakra + make the bija sound."}],warnings:["This is intense. Don\u2019t push through discomfort.","If you skip a chakra and end on the wrong nostril, do a makeup round.","You can always focus on just one or two chakras instead."],keyQuote:"Enough pussyfooting around. Today we just do it all."}},{id:12,date:"May 12",title:"Diksha (Initiation)",subtitle:"Tantric initiation, lineage, and the self-initiation ritual",content:{overview:"Real Tantra requires initiation (diksha) \u2014 you can\u2019t properly do most practices without it. Initiation establishes lineage connection, opens subtle channels, transmits the energy of the tradition, and makes you eligible for teachings.\n\nThis course takes the non-dual approach: your own awake awareness IS the guru, and the lineage runs directly from you to your Buddha nature.",concepts:[{heading:"What Diksha Does",body:"Lineage connection: links you to an unbroken chain of transmission going back to the source deity. Empowerment: opens your subtle channels, \u201cplugs the lamp into the wall.\u201d Samaya vows: ethical commitments. Eligibility: you can now receive teachings and guidance. Authenticity: safeguards the tradition."},{heading:"The Non-Dual Initiation",body:"The final class (Visakh / Buddha Purnima full moon) performed a self-initiation:\n\nThe guru: your own awake awareness / Buddha nature. The lineage: you \u2190 your own awake awareness (direct, no intermediaries). The mantra: Soham Hansaha. The seed syllable of the vow: HREEM.\n\nThe vow: to recognize your own non-difference from awake awareness in this lifetime. And once recognized, to continue deepening that recognition every day for the rest of life."}],practices:[{name:"The Vow Practice",type:"meditation",instructions:"This can be done daily as a recommitment:\n\nWash hands and face. Light a candle if available. Pray to your own awake awareness to cleanse your nadis. Do your full Nadi Shodhana practice.\n\nUsing the mantra Soham Hansaha, invite awake awareness into your entire being. Feel it filling the central channel.\n\nFlip perspective: not just energy in the channel, but the channel arises in awake awareness. The body arises in awake awareness. The world arises in awake awareness.\n\nRepeat HREEM three times aloud. Renew the vow. Sit in the view."}],warnings:[],keyQuote:"The lineage goes back directly from you to your own awake awareness. That\u2019s it. As direct as it could possibly be."}}];

const PRACTICE_SEQUENCE={heading:"Recommended Daily Practice Sequence",body:"Based on the cumulative teaching across all 12 classes:\n\n1. Kapalabhati \u2014 3\u20135 rounds (Bhastrika + full exhale + full inhale + hold + left nostril exhale). Optional: add 1-second Maha Bandha at the full exhale.\n\n2. Full Nadi Shodhana \u2014 Ascend and descend through chakras with elemental bijas, kumbhaka (at your ratio), and bandhas. 3\u201310 minutes depending on capacity.\n\n3. Brief Bhastrika \u2014 Re-oxygenate if needed.\n\n4. Sit \u2014 5\u201310 minutes feeling the energy, then transition to your meditation practice (shamatha \u2192 vipassana, or whatever your system is).\n\nThe pranayama IS shamatha. It gets you concentrated, clear, and energized. Then you meditate from that place.\n\nThroughout the day: walking mantra. Replace default mode chatter with your chosen mantra.\n\nPeriodically: chakra meditation with bijas, extended single-chakra work, visualization practice.\n\nSequence principle: gross \u2192 subtle. Pranayama (physical) \u2192 mantra (mental) \u2192 visualization (imaginal) \u2192 meditation (open)."};

